# Branching & PR Strategy (Pre-v1)

## Base branch

- `main` is the default base branch until v1.
- Start all work branches from `main` unless a maintainer explicitly asks for a different base.
- Open pull requests to `main` unless the user explicitly requests another target.

## Protected main workflow

- Do not push directly to `main` for product changes.
- Land changes through pull requests only, with required checks green.
- Keep branch protection active for `main` (no direct pushes, approval required, required checks required).

## Branch scope and naming

- One phase (or tightly coupled pair) per branch.
- Branch names: `feat/<slug>`, `fix/<slug>`, `chore/<slug>`, or `agent/<agent-id>/<task-slug>/<run-id>`.
- Keep branch scope narrow to reduce review risk and rollback complexity.

## PR and merge requirements

- Use conventional-commit style PR titles: `type(scope): short description`.
- Keep PRs reviewable (soft cap ~400 non-generated changed lines unless justified).
- If stacked, include `blocked-by:#<PR>` in downstream PR bodies.
- Prefer squash merge unless the user or repository policy says otherwise.

## Rollback readiness

- Any schema/data-impacting PR must include rollback notes and risk statement.

## Post-v1 note

- After v1, integration branch strategy may change; this rule applies to pre-v1 workflow.
